        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging requirements:
To map the distributions of different molecular emission lines at unprecedented detail, we require a moderately good uv coverage (as expected in ALMA Cycle 2), and an angular resolution of 1''. This is well-matched to the apparent size (1-3'') of the structures in our ATCA HCN map (Figure 3a), and will be achieved in Band 7 using the compact array configuration C34-1. Higher angular resolution, although desirable, would result in prohibitive integration times to reach the necessarry sensitivity for detection of new molecular species. 

The dimensions of the Homunculus are 16''x8'', but all individual molecular structures resolved to-date span only ~ 0.2-1'' in their narrowest dimension and up to about 8'' in their broadest dimension. Thus, we do not expect to suffer from significant flux losses as a result of lack of short spacings (the maximum recoverable scale in Band 7 C34-1 is 7.6''). With an 18'' field of view of view, ALMA is ideally suited to mapping the whole Homunculus in a single pointing in Band 7.

The continuum emission of eta Car is bright at sub-mm wavelengths (~ 50 Jy). However, this is predominantly confined to a compact source around the central star(s) (Figure 3a), and will not present a significant problem with respect to the dynamic range required to detect weak (~ 100 mJy) emission features throughout the Homunculus.


Correlator setup:
Our lines of interest are distributed quite uniformly across the spectral range 345-373 GHz. To observe each line independently would require at least five correlator settings.  Thus, our observations are optimally performed in spectral scan mode. Complete frequency coverage also allows us to fulfill another important objective: searching for new, previously unobserved species around eta Car. Numerous species plausibly present in eta Car have strong transitions within this range, and a spectral scan is the most effective way to search for them.  Confirmation of new species (such as MgNC and FeCN, and other unknown species) will require detections of multiple lines, which is facilitated by the proposed broad spectral scan. 
 
Our ATCA data shows kinematic structures as narrow as 10 km/s, but narrower structures are likely present. High spectral resolution (1 km/s) is therefore required in order to fully resolve the spectral lines and to characterise the three-dimensional distributions of the detected molecules. Broad bandwidth (&gt;1500 km/s) is justified by the fact that our Herschel CO spectra show line wings out to +-500-800 km/s.

Spectral averaging of two helps to keep the data rate within Cycle 2 policy limits, without sacrificing resolution.


Requested sensitivity:
Table 1 shows predicted peak brightness temperatures for selected emission lines of the main species of interest in this proposal. These have been calculated based on a combination of our 3 mm ATCA HCN observations of eta Car, single-dish (APEX) observations, and chemical modeling of the inner wind. They represent likely line strengths in ALMA Band 7 for material in the eastern HCN peak identified in our ATCA map (Figure 3a). To produce detailed, high-fidelity maps the known species across the homunculus (CO, HCN, HCO+, N2H+) will require high signal-to-noise ratios (preferrably ~ 1000). This will be achieved with an RMS sensitivity of 25 mK per 3 km/s resolution element. Such high sensitivity is expected to permit mapping of these species not only in the inner regions of eta Car where triatomic molecules have already been detected, but also towards the less chemically well-studied outer Homunculus and the "skin" where H2 resides. 

From our chemical models, we estimate the peak HC3N, CH3CN and N2O brightness temperatures to be ~ 300 mK. Again, 25 mK per resolution element will be sufficient to obtain robust (&gt;~10 sigma) detections of these species. This high-sensitivity spectral scan is also a requirement for detecting (and mapping) less abundant/presently unknown molecules.

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
