    <prp:abstract>In 1843, Eta Carinae underwent a colossal outburst, producing the dusty, bipolar Homunculus nebula. Large amounts of molecular gas were recently found around eta Car, the origin of which provides a challenge for our understanding of LBV star chemistry. Spectrally and spatially resolved observations are required in order to determine the origin of the molecular emission, and to search for other complex molecules predicted by our chemical models. Understanding the origin of the observed molecules -- and how they form on such rapid timescales -- will pave the way towards a more complete understanding of the environment surrounding Eta Carinae and other massive stars. Observations of multiple lines from various molecules, combined with our chemical models, will allow us to answer fundamental questions including: Where and how are molecules formed in eta Car? What is the temperature and density structure of the molecular gas? What different chemical regimes are present in the stellar ejecta?  The proposed spectral scan will permit a thorough examination of eta Car's chemistry, elucidating the processes that shaped the Homunculus nebula, and LBV ejecta throughout the universe.</prp:abstract>
